Vonage : CEO unafraid of big shift in Holmdel company's plans 



































0






07/20/2017 | 04:46pm CEST 


Send by mail :
Last Name :
Name :
From* :
To* :
(You can enter multiple email addresses separated by commas)
Message :
*Required fields





July 20--HOLMDEL -- The company had tried door number one, going after the residential market. It could pursue door number two, going after the business market. The board asked him for his thoughts on door number three.
"I said, 'I don't think there is a door number three,'" Masarek said. "'I think we can win door number two.'"
It must have been a trick question, because Masarek was hired. Now three years into his plan, he is revamping Vonage, turning the company known for its inexpensive telephone service and nearly incessant advertising campaign in a new direction, focusing on the business market.
More: Holmdel tech entrepreneur inspired by running his Rutgers fraternity
To get there, he is trying to overhaul the company's culture -- a prospect that could give it a more prominent role in rebuilding the Jersey Shore's technology industry. For more on innovation at the Shore, watch the videos at the top of the story.
Vonage renewed its lease, keeping it here until at least 2023. It redecorated its office, complete with massage chairs and music-themed conference rooms. It recruited interns at New Jersey colleges.
"Vonage is at a historic point," George Sutton, an analyst with Craig-Hallum Capital Group said in a research report in May. With the company's transition, "the math gets to be more and more compelling."
Shaky start
Vonage has nearly 2,000 employees, including about 700 who work at its 88-acre campus on Main Street.
It was founded in 2001, offering Voice over Internet Protocol (VOIP) telephone service that allowed unlimited long-distance calls for $24.99 a month, shaking up traditional telecommunications companies that once charged for long-distance calls by the minute.
Vonage flooded the market with advertising; in 2005 it was the nation's top advertiser on the internet, helping it become a household name. It had more than 2 million customers.
But it ran into problems, too: consumer complaints; patent lawsuits by Verizon Communications and other phone companies; and dwindling cash to pay off debt to name a few.
The company caught a break when it refinanced its debt during the worst of the recession in 2008, a sign that its business was strong enough to survive. But less than a decade later, it faces another obstacles: Consumers are ditching their landlines, along with Vonage's service, in favor of wireless phones.
More: What smart home technology is a good investment?
More: UPDATE: Holmdel has no knowledge of Route 35 supermarket plan
Door No. 2
Vonage is turning to businesses to make up for it. It made a splash a year ago, when it acquired Nexmo, a San Francisco technology company for $230 million. With it, Vonage can provide companies with a voice, video and messaging system through the cloud.
An example: A customer who uses their app to book a flight and runs into trouble can call a customer service agent for help, but the agent will have to start from square one.
But Vonage says it can now provide a system so that the agent will have all of the customer's information -- from their history to what they are trying to do -- when they hop on the line.
It takes away a common source of frustration for customers who are tripped up by online instructions, only to hear an agent say: "Hi, can I get your name/phone number/ZIP code? How can I help you?"
And it opens a new market for Vonage.
More: Vydia, Symbolic, Safe-Com: Top innovative Shore tech companies
More: Asbury's Legemdary looks to shake up diamond industry with app
"There's not a company I talk to today that isn't trying to figure out how to create an enhanced customer experience," said Zeus Kerravala, a consultant with ZK Research in Westminster, Massachusetts.
Masarek, 56, lives in Milford, Connecticut, with his wife, Patti, and keeps an apartment in Red Bank. They have two adult children, daughter, Jordan, and son, Jared.
A triathlete, Masarek in 2002 co-founded Quickoffice, which allowed consumers to use Microsoft Office products like Word on Excel on any mobile operating system. They sold the company to Google in 2012.
Masarek became CEO of Vonage in 2015, when business customers made up just 10 percent of the company's revenue. This year, they are on pace to make up more than half.
Masarek sat down with the Asbury Park Press this week at the company's headquarters -- which includes free soda, motivational quotes on closet doors from Thomas Edison and Albert Einstein, and a Frank Sinatra conference room that looks like a cigar lounge -- to talk about the company's new direction.
Five questions:
Why leave Google for Vonage?
I worked in the Mountain View headquarters and I was kind of too young to retire and was getting CEO inquires that weren't particularly interesting. And then this one came along and I was kind of fascinated by the opportunity to almost reposition this almost iconic consumer brand.
Why focus on businesses instead of consumers?
Residential is still incredibly important to us, and it's still there and it's profitable, but as home phone usage is in decline, our kids will unlikely have home phones as everybody moves to mobile and such, you have the number of residential home phone subscribers is down from what it once was ... (But the underlying) network doesn't care if you are calling home to your grandmother or if it's a business call. Our network, which is the biggest piece of the cost, is shared between residential and business.
Why would businesses be interested?
Say a customer with 500 restaurants is trying to increase its take-out business. They had users start to text in orders. "I want two doubles and fries." The problem is, you don't know whether the customer is going to walk in in five minutes or 35 minutes. So you don't know when to cook it. So you cook it in five minutes and the guy walks in in 35 minutes, and it's sitting in the heat lamp, soggy french fries.
Using our tools, what they've done is, they've geo-fenced each of those 500 restaurants. It's software that does this. It says, 'I want to have an estimate, basically a circumference around the physical restaurant that basically tells me that a driver is five minutes away. ...' When you cross into the geo fence, it sends ... a message to the restaurant that says, 'Start cooking Mr. Smith's order.' And then sends a followup text message to Mr. Smith that says, don't even come in the restaurant, come in the two designated spots for takeout and we'll bring the food out for them. Here you've used communications as a way to improve the restaurant chain's business imperative to build the takeout business.
What did you learn at Google?
Google has done a remarkable job of hiring great talent, managing them well, delivering great results, which has led to hiring more great talent, managing it well, more great results. Very virtuous cycle. We want to do the same thing here; create Vonage as a destination place to work.
How difficult is that to replicate that culture, not at a startup, but at a 16-year-old company?
Growth and comfort don't co-exist. It's hard. It's discomforting to people to grow. People tend to want to come to work and do what they did yesterday just a little better than they did today. That's not being innovative. ...You have to set the mission where we're going, rinse and repeat on the message, but have the right talent to do it. It's not coming out of my head. I mean, I've got broad shoulders, but not that broad. You've got to bring in great people in order to be able to do that.
Michael L. Diamond; 732-643-4038; mdiamond@gannettnj.com
___
(c)2017 the Asbury Park Press (Neptune, N.J.)
Visit the Asbury Park Press (Neptune, N.J.) at www.app.com
Distributed by Tribune Content Agency, LLC.© Tribune Content Agency, source Regional News




















































